1
00:03:13,526 --> 00:03:15,662
[Faint Conversation]

2
00:03:15,795 --> 00:03:18,787
- He had a live-in nurse but...
- She was nothing but a bother.

3
00:03:18,898 --> 00:03:21,799
I not like her.
Mr. Jimmy not like her.

4
00:03:21,901 --> 00:03:24,802
It be better if you
live in again, Mr. David.

5
00:03:24,904 --> 00:03:26,804
- Hanna, stop it.
- Shh.

6
00:03:26,906 --> 00:03:29,841
If there's any emergency,
you call me in New York.

7
00:03:29,943 --> 00:03:31,535
[Hanna Whispers]
Yes, I call.

8
00:03:31,644 --> 00:03:34,044
- Uh, Mr. Jimmy, more coffee?
- What?

9
00:03:36,916 --> 00:03:38,816
Oh, well, yes.
Why not?

10
00:03:38,918 --> 00:03:41,443
Just half a cup, Hanna.

11
00:03:42,922 --> 00:03:45,618
Isn't Hanna a peach,
hmm?

12
00:03:49,362 --> 00:03:51,262
[Chuckles]

13
00:03:51,364 --> 00:03:54,492
But she tells me that
you haven't been sleeping very well.

14
00:03:54,601 --> 00:03:57,502
Well, is these ridiculous
pills they prescribe.

15
00:03:57,604 --> 00:03:59,504
For instance, the Luminal.

16
00:03:59,606 --> 00:04:03,064
If I take it the next day
I go around as stupid as a stone,

17
00:04:03,176 --> 00:04:07,112
and if I don't take it
then my minïs going off
in a hundred directions at once.

18
00:04:07,247 --> 00:04:08,942
Then take the Luminal.

19
00:04:09,082 --> 00:04:13,815
[Sighs] Well, yes, but today
I wanted to be alert for your visit,

20
00:04:13,920 --> 00:04:18,152
particularly as I saw
so little of you at the hospital.

21
00:04:18,258 --> 00:04:21,659
Jimmy, look, I'm sorry, but with
this picture and two difficult stars...

22
00:04:21,761 --> 00:04:23,661
[Laughing]
Dear David.

23
00:04:23,763 --> 00:04:27,255
Is no pleasure making you feel guilty.
Go on, off you go.

24
00:04:27,367 --> 00:04:30,268
You don't want to miss
your aeroplane.

25
00:04:42,615 --> 00:04:45,083
- I like your new Cezanne.
- Oh.

26
00:04:45,218 --> 00:04:47,345
Well.

27
00:04:47,487 --> 00:04:48,852
Good-bye, Hanna.

28
00:04:51,324 --> 00:04:53,224
I get the door.

29
00:04:53,326 --> 00:04:55,988
- [Door Opens]
- [Clears Throat]

30
00:04:56,095 --> 00:04:58,063
- [Door Closes]
- [Motor Cranking]

31
00:05:02,702 --> 00:05:05,330
[Whistle Blowing]

32
00:05:16,649 --> 00:05:20,176
- [Lawn Mower Continues Running]
- Who is this new yard man?

33
00:05:20,320 --> 00:05:22,982
Mr. Boom... I-I don't...
Something "B."

34
00:05:23,089 --> 00:05:26,115
I hire him while you
were in the hospital.

35
00:05:26,225 --> 00:05:28,386
He came cheap.

36
00:05:34,901 --> 00:05:38,462
go ting-a-ling-a-ling?

37
00:05:38,571 --> 00:05:40,869
? For you but not for me?

38
00:05:40,973 --> 00:05:43,703
? O death, where is
thy sting-a-ling-a-ling?

39
00:05:43,810 --> 00:05:47,576
? Grave
where thy victory??

40
00:05:47,714 --> 00:05:50,148
Good morning.

41
00:05:50,283 --> 00:05:52,911
My name is Whale.
This is my house.

42
00:05:53,052 --> 00:05:56,613
- And your name is?
- Boone. Clay Boone.

43
00:05:56,723 --> 00:06:00,056
I couldn't help but notice
your tattoo.

44
00:06:00,159 --> 00:06:04,061
That motto..."Death before dishonor."
What does it mean?

45
00:06:04,163 --> 00:06:07,326
- It just means that I was a marine.
- Ah, the Marines.

46
00:06:07,433 --> 00:06:08,832
I suppose
you served in Korea.

47
00:06:08,935 --> 00:06:10,903
[Grunts]
Yeah.

48
00:06:13,940 --> 00:06:16,170
Well, I'm gonna
get back to work.

49
00:06:16,275 --> 00:06:19,176
Well, when you're through
feel free to use the pool.

50
00:06:19,278 --> 00:06:21,212
And we're quite
informal here.

51
00:06:21,314 --> 00:06:24,215
No need to worry about
a bathing suit.

52
00:06:24,317 --> 00:06:26,547
I got another lawn to do
this afternoon.

53
00:06:26,652 --> 00:06:29,348
Oh, well,
then some other time.

54
00:06:29,455 --> 00:06:31,514
Yes,
keep up the good work.

55
00:06:32,859 --> 00:06:35,259
?? [Whale Whistling]

56
00:06:49,876 --> 00:06:51,776
[Sighs]

57
00:07:23,376 --> 00:07:26,106
- [Rain Falling]
- [Woman] Jimmy!

58
00:07:26,212 --> 00:07:29,147
- Privy needs cleanin'.
- I have me class tonight.

59
00:07:29,248 --> 00:07:32,149
Don't get above yourself.
Leave the drawing to the artists.

60
00:07:32,251 --> 00:07:34,219
Quite so, Mum.

61
00:07:35,588 --> 00:07:37,488
- To the privy.
- [Clicks Heels]

62
00:07:37,590 --> 00:07:40,115
"Quite so"?
Jimmy Whale.

63
00:07:40,226 --> 00:07:42,786
Who are you
to put on airs?

64
00:07:45,298 --> 00:07:47,198
Jimmy Whale.

65
00:08:01,714 --> 00:08:04,547
- Is there iced tea, Hanna?
- Yes, Mr. Jimmy.

66
00:08:04,650 --> 00:08:06,982
- Ah, cucumber sandwiches.
- Mmm.

67
00:08:07,086 --> 00:08:09,987
An interview, after so many years.
Very exciting.

68
00:08:10,089 --> 00:08:13,217
Oh, don't be daft. Is just a student
from the university.

69
00:08:13,326 --> 00:08:15,226
- Mm-hmm.
- [Doorbell Rings]

70
00:08:19,532 --> 00:08:21,591
[Man Talking, Faint]

71
00:08:21,701 --> 00:08:23,601
[Hanna]
This way, please.

72
00:08:27,340 --> 00:08:29,501
- Mr. Kay, sir.
- Huh?

73
00:08:29,609 --> 00:08:32,009
Oh, yes, of course.
Mr. Kay.

74
00:08:32,111 --> 00:08:34,579
I'd almost forgotten.

75
00:08:34,714 --> 00:08:36,614
My tea-time guest.

76
00:08:36,716 --> 00:08:39,184
Mr. Whale,
this is such an honor.

77
00:08:39,318 --> 00:08:42,219
You're one of my favorite
all-time directors.

78
00:08:42,321 --> 00:08:44,755
[Laughs]
I can't believe I'm meeting you.

79
00:08:44,857 --> 00:08:46,722
No, I don't suppose
you can.

80
00:08:46,826 --> 00:08:49,226
And this is your house.
Ah!

81
00:08:49,328 --> 00:08:51,592
The house of Frankenstein.

82
00:08:51,697 --> 00:08:55,599
I thought you'd live in
a great big villa or a mansion.

83
00:08:55,701 --> 00:08:58,568
Ah, well,
one likes to live simply.

84
00:08:58,671 --> 00:09:01,435
I know. People's movies
aren't their lives.

85
00:09:03,042 --> 00:09:06,375
[lmitates Frankenstein's Monster]
"Love dead. Hate living."

86
00:09:06,479 --> 00:09:09,004
[High-Pitched Giggle]

87
00:09:09,148 --> 00:09:13,482
Thas my favorite line in my favorite
movie of yours: Bride of Frankenstein.

88
00:09:13,586 --> 00:09:16,180
Is it indeed?
Yes.

89
00:09:16,289 --> 00:09:19,554
Hanna, I think we're going to
take our tea down by the swimming pool.

90
00:09:20,860 --> 00:09:23,420
Would that be good for you,
Mr. Kay?

91
00:09:23,529 --> 00:09:25,190
Sure.

92
00:09:25,298 --> 00:09:28,199
- Well, lead on, won't you.
- Mm-hmm. [Giggles]

93
00:09:28,301 --> 00:09:31,202
I love the great horror films,
and yours are the best.

94
00:09:31,304 --> 00:09:33,704
The Old Dark House.
The Invisible Man.

95
00:09:33,806 --> 00:09:36,206
They have style,
and they're funny!

96
00:09:36,309 --> 00:09:40,769
So, Mr. Kay,
what do you want to know?

97
00:09:40,913 --> 00:09:42,778
Everything.

98
00:09:42,882 --> 00:09:44,782
Just start
at the beginning.

99
00:09:44,884 --> 00:09:46,977
Well, I was born
just outside London,

100
00:09:47,119 --> 00:09:50,452
the only son of a minister
who was also a schoolmaster.

101
00:09:50,556 --> 00:09:54,048
Grandpapa was a bishop,
Church of...

102
00:09:54,160 --> 00:09:56,492
[Bell Tolling]

103
00:09:56,596 --> 00:09:59,724
Stop lagging behind, Jimmy.
We'll be late for church.

104
00:09:59,832 --> 00:10:02,164
[Father]
Come on!

105
00:10:02,268 --> 00:10:04,236
Stop lallygagging!

106
00:10:04,337 --> 00:10:06,237
[Bell Continues Tolling]

107
00:10:06,339 --> 00:10:09,240
Straighten up, son.
They'll think you're a Nancy boy.

108
00:10:09,342 --> 00:10:12,334
[Men, Women Talking,
Faint]

109
00:10:15,615 --> 00:10:18,175
Mr. Whale?

110
00:10:19,585 --> 00:10:22,019
Your father
was a schoolmaster?

111
00:10:22,154 --> 00:10:26,488
Yes, of course.
And I was going to go up to Oxford.

112
00:10:26,592 --> 00:10:31,325
[Sighs] But the war broke out
and I never made it.

113
00:10:31,430 --> 00:10:34,866
You cannot imagine what life was like
after the Armistice.

114
00:10:34,967 --> 00:10:37,128
The '20s in London.

115
00:10:37,236 --> 00:10:40,137
A break with everything dour
and respectable.

116
00:10:40,239 --> 00:10:42,366
I had a knack
with pencil and paper,

117
00:10:42,475 --> 00:10:45,376
so I was hired to design sets
for stage productions.

118
00:10:45,478 --> 00:10:47,810
Ah.

119
00:10:51,484 --> 00:10:53,918
Yes.
Help yourself.

120
00:10:54,020 --> 00:10:56,215
Cucumber sandwiches.

121
00:10:56,322 --> 00:10:59,291
[Sighs]
Thank you, Hanna.

122
00:10:59,392 --> 00:11:01,827
And you can go now.

123
00:11:01,961 --> 00:11:03,656
There was one play
in particular,

124
00:11:03,763 --> 00:11:07,995
a beautiful, grim study of war
called Journey's End.

125
00:11:08,134 --> 00:11:11,729
Every experienced director
turned it down. Not commercial.

126
00:11:11,871 --> 00:11:13,930
So I offered myself.

127
00:11:14,073 --> 00:11:16,940
Journey's End made the careers
of everyone associated with it.

128
00:11:17,043 --> 00:11:19,910
It was only a matter of time
before Hollywood beckoned.

129
00:11:20,012 --> 00:11:23,914
How much longer before
we get to the horror movies?

130
00:11:24,016 --> 00:11:28,612
Am I right in assuming, Mr. Kay, that
it is not me that you are interested in,

131
00:11:28,721 --> 00:11:30,746
but only
my horror pictures?

132
00:11:32,224 --> 00:11:35,990
No, but is the horror movies
you'll be remembered for.

133
00:11:36,095 --> 00:11:37,824
I'm not dead yet, Mr. Kay.

134
00:11:37,930 --> 00:11:41,093
No.
Uh, I never said you were.

135
00:11:41,233 --> 00:11:43,667
Or w-will be soon.

136
00:11:43,803 --> 00:11:47,500
So, Journey's End
brought you to Hollywood.

137
00:11:47,606 --> 00:11:49,972
I've got a little proposal.

138
00:11:51,310 --> 00:11:53,710
This line of questioning
is getting old.

139
00:11:53,813 --> 00:11:56,714
- Don't you think?
- I don't mind.

140
00:11:56,816 --> 00:11:58,716
Well, I do.

141
00:11:58,818 --> 00:12:01,616
Les make it
more interesting for me.

142
00:12:01,721 --> 00:12:05,122
I will answer truthfully
any question that you put to me,

143
00:12:05,224 --> 00:12:10,218
and in return, for each answer
you will remove an article of clothing.

144
00:12:13,999 --> 00:12:15,557
I thi...

145
00:12:15,701 --> 00:12:17,601
Thas funny, Mr. Whale.

146
00:12:17,703 --> 00:12:19,603
Yes, it is, isn't it?

147
00:12:19,705 --> 00:12:22,299
My life
as a game of strip poker.

148
00:12:22,408 --> 00:12:24,308
Shall we play?

149
00:12:24,410 --> 00:12:26,207
So the rumors are true then.

150
00:12:26,312 --> 00:12:28,712
Oh?
What rumors would those be?

151
00:12:29,949 --> 00:12:31,849
That you were forced
to retire...

152
00:12:31,951 --> 00:12:33,851
because of,

153
00:12:33,953 --> 00:12:35,978
um, a sex scandal.

154
00:12:36,088 --> 00:12:39,455
A homosexual scandal,
you mean.

155
00:12:39,558 --> 00:12:42,152
For me to answer
a question of that magnitude,

156
00:12:42,261 --> 00:12:44,855
you'll have to remove
both your shoes and socks.

157
00:12:44,964 --> 00:12:47,057
You're a dirty old man.

158
00:12:47,199 --> 00:12:48,564
Oh.

159
00:12:53,139 --> 00:12:58,042
Oh, it is kind of you
to indulge your elders in their vices,

160
00:12:59,311 --> 00:13:01,609
just as I indulge the young
in theirs.

161
00:13:15,628 --> 00:13:18,859
No, there was no scandal.

162
00:13:18,964 --> 00:13:20,898
My only other vice.

163
00:13:22,501 --> 00:13:26,232
I expect you'd like
a fuller answer to that question.

164
00:13:26,338 --> 00:13:28,806
Ill cost you your jacket.

165
00:13:30,943 --> 00:13:32,774
Too warm
for a jacket anyway.

166
00:13:36,315 --> 00:13:39,648
You must understand
how Hollywood was 20 years ago.

167
00:13:39,752 --> 00:13:43,347
If you were a star nobody cared
a tinker's cuss who you slept with,

168
00:13:43,455 --> 00:13:46,891
so long as you kept it
out of the papers.

169
00:13:46,992 --> 00:13:52,828
As for us directors, well,
outside Hollywood who even knows
who George Cukor is,

170
00:13:52,965 --> 00:13:56,924
much less what he gets up to
with those boys from the malt shops?

171
00:13:57,069 --> 00:14:00,766
George Cukor?
Who made A Star is Born?

172
00:14:00,873 --> 00:14:03,899
Take off your shirt,
and I'll tell you all about it.

173
00:14:12,952 --> 00:14:16,854
George is famous for
his Saturday dinner parties.

174
00:14:16,956 --> 00:14:20,858
Great writers, artists,
society folk,

175
00:14:20,960 --> 00:14:23,588
all rubbing elbows
with Hollywood royalty.

176
00:14:23,696 --> 00:14:26,665
But how many of those
oh-so-proper people...

177
00:14:26,765 --> 00:14:29,666
know about the Sunday brunches
that follow?

178
00:14:29,768 --> 00:14:33,169
Armies of trade
eating up the leftovers,

179
00:14:33,272 --> 00:14:36,799
followed by some strenuous
fun and frolic in the pool. [Snickers]

180
00:14:38,010 --> 00:14:40,672
Can we talk about
the horror movies now?

181
00:14:40,779 --> 00:14:42,610
Certainly.

182
00:14:42,715 --> 00:14:45,616
Is there anything in particular
that you want to know?

183
00:14:45,718 --> 00:14:48,186
Will you tell me
everything you remember...

184
00:14:48,287 --> 00:14:50,187
about making Frankenstein?

185
00:14:50,289 --> 00:14:52,587
[Whispers]
Ohh.

186
00:14:54,226 --> 00:14:56,490
Can that count
as one question?

187
00:14:56,595 --> 00:14:59,962
- Of course.
- I can't believe I'm doing this.

188
00:15:09,909 --> 00:15:12,207
Just like going swimming,
isn't it?

189
00:15:12,311 --> 00:15:15,212
Well, maybe you'd like a swim
when we're through.

190
00:15:15,314 --> 00:15:18,943
I don't swim myself,
so the pool tends to go to waste.

191
00:15:19,051 --> 00:15:20,951
Okay.
Frankenstein.

192
00:15:21,053 --> 00:15:23,783
Who came up with
the monster's makeup and look?

193
00:15:23,889 --> 00:15:26,790
Oh, my idea, mostly,
from my sketches.

194
00:15:26,892 --> 00:15:28,792
Big, heavy brow.

195
00:15:28,894 --> 00:15:32,352
The head flat on top so you could take
out the old brain and put in the new...

196
00:15:32,464 --> 00:15:34,398
like tinned beef.

197
00:15:34,500 --> 00:15:38,834
[Laughs] He's one of
the great images of the 20th century,

198
00:15:38,938 --> 00:15:41,372
more important
than the Mona Lisa.

199
00:15:41,473 --> 00:15:43,407
Oh, don't be daft.

200
00:15:43,509 --> 00:15:46,342
Is just makeup and padding
and a big actor.

201
00:15:46,445 --> 00:15:48,675
Is hardly the Mona Lisa.

202
00:15:48,781 --> 00:15:51,477
Boris Karloff.

203
00:15:51,583 --> 00:15:54,484
How did you ever think of casting him
as the Monster?

204
00:15:56,622 --> 00:15:59,819
He'd never even starred
in a movie before that.

205
00:16:04,229 --> 00:16:06,129
Mr. Whale?

206
00:16:07,766 --> 00:16:10,200
Is something the matter?

207
00:16:12,237 --> 00:16:14,637
- [Grunts]
- Mr. Whale?

208
00:16:14,740 --> 00:16:16,640
Please excuse me.

209
00:16:17,910 --> 00:16:19,571
Are you all right?

210
00:16:19,678 --> 00:16:21,578
[Groaning]

211
00:16:21,680 --> 00:16:23,978
Just...

212
00:16:24,083 --> 00:16:26,313
need to lie down.

213
00:16:26,418 --> 00:16:30,081
- Studio. There's a day bed
in the studio.
- [Gasps]

214
00:16:30,189 --> 00:16:34,091
Oh, my God. Mr. Whale,
wh-whas wrong? Is it your heart?

215
00:16:34,193 --> 00:16:36,491
No, head, not heart.

216
00:16:41,900 --> 00:16:44,801
Water.
Glass is in sink.

217
00:16:44,903 --> 00:16:46,803
Which ones?
I bring them all.

218
00:16:46,905 --> 00:16:48,805
Luminal.

219
00:17:05,591 --> 00:17:08,685
Mr. Kay,
you're not dressed.

220
00:17:10,996 --> 00:17:12,896
I was gonna go swimming.

221
00:17:13,032 --> 00:17:14,761
So you were.

222
00:17:14,900 --> 00:17:18,529
Mmm.
You should probably go home.

223
00:17:20,272 --> 00:17:23,298
- [Clicking Tongue]
- [Screen Door Opens]

224
00:17:24,410 --> 00:17:26,310
[Door Closes]

225
00:17:26,412 --> 00:17:28,312
[Inhales Deeply]

226
00:17:28,414 --> 00:17:30,473
You must think I'm terrible,
Hanna.

227
00:17:30,582 --> 00:17:32,812
I don't think
you're anything anymore.

228
00:17:32,918 --> 00:17:36,319
Just back from the hospital,
already you're chasing after boys.

229
00:17:36,422 --> 00:17:39,823
Oh, shut up.
All we did was talk.

230
00:17:41,393 --> 00:17:44,829
Perhaps I should get you uphill
before the pills knock you cold.

231
00:17:44,930 --> 00:17:47,023
No, no, no, no, no.
Please, no.

232
00:17:47,166 --> 00:17:49,066
Let me stay here.

233
00:17:59,945 --> 00:18:01,936
Thank you.

234
00:18:05,184 --> 00:18:09,587
- [Soldiers Shouting]
- [Gunfire, Bombs Exploding]

235
00:18:09,688 --> 00:18:12,589
- [Gunfire Continues]
- [Man] Quiet on the set, please.

236
00:18:12,691 --> 00:18:15,091
- [Father] You're a disgrace!
- [Man] Mr. Whale?

237
00:18:15,194 --> 00:18:18,288
- [Mother]
Jimmy, privy needs cleanin'.
- Mr. Whale.

238
00:18:22,234 --> 00:18:23,895
Open your eyes.

239
00:18:25,771 --> 00:18:27,534
Now look left.

240
00:18:27,639 --> 00:18:30,767
Thas right.
And breathe out.

241
00:18:33,145 --> 00:18:35,773
Good.
Les see what we've got.

242
00:18:35,881 --> 00:18:37,781
You're a lucky man,
Mr. Whale.

243
00:18:37,883 --> 00:18:39,783
Whatever damage was done
by your stroke,

244
00:18:39,885 --> 00:18:42,786
it left your motor abilities
relatively unimpaired.

245
00:18:42,888 --> 00:18:45,618
Yes, Dr. Payne, but what about
from the neck upwards?

246
00:18:45,724 --> 00:18:48,716
- Whas the story there?
- Thas what I'm trying to explain.

247
00:18:48,827 --> 00:18:51,057
The central nervous system
selects items...

248
00:18:51,163 --> 00:18:53,063
from a constant storm
of sensations.

249
00:18:53,198 --> 00:18:55,325
Whatever was killed
in your stroke...

250
00:18:55,467 --> 00:18:59,665
seems to have short-circuited
this mechanism.

251
00:18:59,771 --> 00:19:03,442
So you're saying there's an electrical
storm going on inside my head.

252
00:19:03,575 --> 00:19:06,169
Well, thas as good a way
as any to describe it.

253
00:19:06,278 --> 00:19:09,213
- I've seen far worse cases.
- What about all the rest?

254
00:19:09,314 --> 00:19:12,977
The killing headaches.
The phantom smells.

255
00:19:13,118 --> 00:19:15,018
My inability
to close my eyes...

256
00:19:15,120 --> 00:19:18,317
without thinking of
a hundred things simultaneously.

257
00:19:18,423 --> 00:19:23,156
I've never encountered the
olfactory hallucinations before,
but I'm sure they're related.

258
00:19:23,262 --> 00:19:26,254
- So, what do I do?
- Take the Luminal to sleep...

259
00:19:26,365 --> 00:19:28,833
and whenever you feel
an attack coming on.

260
00:19:28,934 --> 00:19:33,337
What you're saying is that this isn't
just a case of resting until I'm better,

261
00:19:33,438 --> 00:19:38,398
but that my condition will continue
to deteriorate until the end of my life.

262
00:19:42,514 --> 00:19:44,914
You will take them all,
Mr. Jimmy.

263
00:19:45,017 --> 00:19:46,917
Yes.
Don't you worry, Hanna.

264
00:19:47,019 --> 00:19:48,919
- Good night.
- Thank you.

265
00:20:10,042 --> 00:20:13,239
Ohh! Oh!
[Whispers Prayer]

266
00:20:13,345 --> 00:20:16,803
Ohh!
[Continues Praying]

267
00:20:25,457 --> 00:20:26,947
[Equipment Thuds]

268
00:20:31,263 --> 00:20:33,731
[Equipment Rattling]

269
00:20:35,767 --> 00:20:37,792
[Clay Whispers]
Shit.

270
00:20:43,442 --> 00:20:45,842
Everything all right,
Mr. Boone?

271
00:20:45,944 --> 00:20:49,004
Yeah, sorry. I didn't mean
to disturb you. It got away from me.

272
00:20:49,147 --> 00:20:54,346
I was just going to buzz Hanna
to bring down some iced tea.

273
00:20:54,453 --> 00:20:57,354
I'd like it very much
if you'd join me.

274
00:20:57,456 --> 00:21:00,653
I kinda stink to high heaven
right now.

275
00:21:00,759 --> 00:21:03,489
Let me ask Hanna
to bring tea for two.

276
00:21:03,595 --> 00:21:05,620
Or would you prefer
a beer?

277
00:21:05,731 --> 00:21:08,632
Uh, no. Thanks.
But tea is fine.

278
00:21:08,734 --> 00:21:11,032
Splendid.

279
00:21:18,310 --> 00:21:19,834
Come in, Mr. Boone.

280
00:21:22,247 --> 00:21:24,147
This is my workshop,
my studio.

281
00:21:24,249 --> 00:21:27,184
Hardly somewhere where a sweaty workman
should feel out of place.

282
00:21:28,620 --> 00:21:31,555
- Are these your paintings?
- Uh, yes. Yes.

283
00:21:33,225 --> 00:21:36,626
Excuse me,
but, uh, are you famous?

284
00:21:36,728 --> 00:21:40,425
Oh, well, you know what they say:
If you have to ask...

285
00:21:40,532 --> 00:21:43,365
Look, I'm just a guy
who cuts lawns, but, uh,

286
00:21:43,468 --> 00:21:45,368
some of these
do look familiar.

287
00:21:45,470 --> 00:21:48,303
Thas because they were familiar
when I painted them.

288
00:21:48,407 --> 00:21:51,205
The one you're looking at
is a copy of a Dutch still life...

289
00:21:51,310 --> 00:21:54,711
done nearly 300 years ago.

290
00:21:54,846 --> 00:21:57,246
And there's a Rembrandt
here somewhere.

291
00:21:57,349 --> 00:22:00,512
Yeah, copies.
l-l... I got ya.

292
00:22:00,619 --> 00:22:06,080
But before I retired, you might say
I had my time in the sun.

293
00:22:06,191 --> 00:22:08,284
Fame, as it were.

294
00:22:08,393 --> 00:22:12,386
- Tell me, do you like motion pictures?
- Yeah, sure. Everybody does.

295
00:22:12,497 --> 00:22:16,126
- Why? Were you an actor?
- Oh, good Lord, no!

296
00:22:16,234 --> 00:22:18,634
No... Well, actually,
I was, in my youth.

297
00:22:18,737 --> 00:22:21,103
But never in Hollywood,
no, no.

298
00:22:21,206 --> 00:22:23,071
No, here I was merely
a director.

299
00:22:24,776 --> 00:22:27,404
Really?

300
00:22:27,512 --> 00:22:29,980
- What were some of your movies?
- Oh, this and that.

301
00:22:30,115 --> 00:22:33,744
The only ones you may have heard of
are the Frankenstein movies.

302
00:22:33,885 --> 00:22:36,945
Frankenstein? And, um, uh,
Bride of Frankenstein?

303
00:22:37,055 --> 00:22:39,956
- And Son of, and the other ones too?
- Uh, no.

304
00:22:40,058 --> 00:22:43,619
I-I just directed the first two.
The others were done by hacks.

305
00:22:43,729 --> 00:22:47,096
Yeah, but still, I mean,
th-those were big movies.

306
00:22:47,199 --> 00:22:49,099
- You must be rich.
- Merely comfortable.

307
00:22:49,201 --> 00:22:53,297
Look, Hanna's here with our
refreshments. Could you get the door?

308
00:22:53,405 --> 00:22:55,930
Y-Yeah. Uh...

309
00:23:04,683 --> 00:23:07,243
How are you feeling,
Mr. Jimmy?

310
00:23:07,386 --> 00:23:09,786
How's your mind today?

311
00:23:09,888 --> 00:23:13,585
My mind is lovely.
And yours?

312
00:23:13,692 --> 00:23:17,492
Uh, remember what
the doctor tells us.

313
00:23:17,596 --> 00:23:21,623
Yes, yes, yes. I have invited
Mr. Boone in merely for a cup of tea.

314
00:23:21,733 --> 00:23:24,133
[Sighs]

315
00:23:24,236 --> 00:23:27,831
We'll have a brief chat,
and then he'll finish the yard.

316
00:23:27,939 --> 00:23:31,340
I am not forgetting
your last "brief chat."

317
00:23:31,443 --> 00:23:34,606
Will you go away?
We can manage.

318
00:23:35,747 --> 00:23:37,305
He looks plenty big.

319
00:23:37,449 --> 00:23:40,247
He won't need my help
if anything goes "flooey."

320
00:23:40,352 --> 00:23:41,751
Go.

321
00:23:43,622 --> 00:23:45,522
Avaunt.

322
00:23:45,624 --> 00:23:47,319
[Chuckles]

323
00:23:51,496 --> 00:23:53,327
Comic maid.

324
00:23:53,432 --> 00:23:55,263
No, she's a love,
Hanna.

325
00:23:55,367 --> 00:23:59,861
But when they're in your employ
too long, servants begin to
think they're married to you.

326
00:23:59,971 --> 00:24:03,668
Please sit down,
and do help yourself, Mr. Boone.

327
00:24:10,482 --> 00:24:13,610
So, what did she mean
by things going all "flooey"?

328
00:24:13,752 --> 00:24:16,516
I'm recently returned
from a spell in hospital.

329
00:24:16,621 --> 00:24:18,350
- What happened?
- Nothing serious.

330
00:24:18,457 --> 00:24:20,891
Touch of stroke.

331
00:24:20,992 --> 00:24:22,892
Huh.

332
00:24:32,370 --> 00:24:35,066
You must excuse
my staring,

333
00:24:35,173 --> 00:24:38,074
but you have
the most marvelous head.

334
00:24:38,176 --> 00:24:40,576
- Huh?
- To an artistic eye.

335
00:24:42,380 --> 00:24:46,248
- Have you ever... modeled?
- What, you mean, like,
posed for pictures?

336
00:24:46,351 --> 00:24:48,876
Sat for an artist?
Been sketched?

337
00:24:49,020 --> 00:24:51,284
Mmm, n...

338
00:24:51,389 --> 00:24:53,823
[Laughs]
Whas to sketch?

339
00:24:53,925 --> 00:24:56,485
You have the most...

340
00:24:56,595 --> 00:24:58,825
architectural skull.

341
00:25:00,031 --> 00:25:03,592
And your nose,
is... very expressive.

342
00:25:05,837 --> 00:25:07,737
- Broke is more like it.
- Mmm.

343
00:25:11,476 --> 00:25:13,376
Oh, sorry to go on
like this.

344
00:25:13,478 --> 00:25:15,378
Is just
the Sunday painter in me.

345
00:25:15,514 --> 00:25:17,414
I quite understand
your refusal.

346
00:25:17,516 --> 00:25:19,416
Is a great deal
to ask of anyone.

347
00:25:19,518 --> 00:25:22,749
You mean, you really
want to draw me?

348
00:25:22,854 --> 00:25:25,288
I would pay for the privilege
of drawing that head.

349
00:25:25,390 --> 00:25:28,120
Is just my head
you want to draw? Nothin' else?

350
00:25:28,226 --> 00:25:30,126
And what are you
suggesting?

351
00:25:30,228 --> 00:25:35,928
That you'll charge extra if I include
a hand or a bit of shoulder?

352
00:25:37,235 --> 00:25:39,135
No, I mean,
you don't wanna...

353
00:25:39,237 --> 00:25:42,331
draw pictures of me
in my birthday suit, do you?

354
00:25:42,440 --> 00:25:45,773
I have no interest
in your body, Mr. Boone.

355
00:25:45,877 --> 00:25:47,936
I can assure you of that.

356
00:25:50,081 --> 00:25:52,606
Well, uh...
[Chuckles]

357
00:25:52,751 --> 00:25:54,651
Yeah.
Why not?

358
00:25:54,753 --> 00:25:57,688
I mean, hell,
I could use the money.

359
00:25:57,822 --> 00:25:59,380
Excellent.

360
00:26:18,610 --> 00:26:21,511
Here are the trade papers
you wanted.

361
00:26:31,623 --> 00:26:34,217
Hello? Hi.
I know you already paid me.

362
00:26:34,326 --> 00:26:37,227
- I'm just here to...
- The master is waiting for you.

363
00:26:37,329 --> 00:26:38,728
He's down in his studio.

364
00:26:38,830 --> 00:26:40,730
Here.
Take this with you.

365
00:26:40,832 --> 00:26:43,733
Uh, I'm sorry, lady.
You're gonna have to take this.

366
00:26:43,835 --> 00:26:46,235
I'm just here
so he can draw my picture.

367
00:26:46,338 --> 00:26:49,705
I'm keeping away. What you are doing
is no business of mine.

368
00:26:49,808 --> 00:26:54,472
- What are you talking about?
- What kind of man are you?
Are you a good man?

369
00:26:54,579 --> 00:26:57,548
Yeah. Something about me
make you think I'm not?

370
00:26:57,649 --> 00:26:58,950
- You will not hurt him?
- I'm gonna sit in a chair,
and he's gonna draw my picture.

371
00:26:58,950 --> 00:27:01,544
- You will not hurt him?
- I'm gonna sit in a chair,
and he's gonna draw my picture.

372
00:27:01,686 --> 00:27:03,586
Is that gonna hurt him?

373
00:27:04,789 --> 00:27:07,087
No.

374
00:27:07,192 --> 00:27:09,092
I'm sorry.

375
00:27:09,194 --> 00:27:12,129
Forget everything I said.
I will take the tray.

376
00:27:12,230 --> 00:27:14,130
Yeah, you do that.

377
00:27:15,367 --> 00:27:18,268
Ah, Mr. Boone.
Come into my parlor.

378
00:27:18,370 --> 00:27:20,497
Ah, Hanna.
Good.

379
00:27:20,605 --> 00:27:22,505
Thank you.

380
00:27:23,742 --> 00:27:25,869
And, Hanna, good-bye.

381
00:27:25,977 --> 00:27:30,380
Now, I'm sure you'd like
to wet your whistle while I work. Hmm?

382
00:27:30,482 --> 00:27:32,382
Oh. Beer.

383
00:27:32,484 --> 00:27:35,419
And we'll take it, uh,
slowly today...

384
00:27:35,520 --> 00:27:38,421
because this is
your first time modeling.

385
00:27:38,523 --> 00:27:40,423
- Oh, hey, did you see this?
- Hmm?

386
00:27:40,525 --> 00:27:43,426
- They're showing one of
your movies tomorrow night.
- You don't say.

387
00:27:43,528 --> 00:27:45,928
- Which picture?
- Uh, Bride of Frankenstein.

388
00:27:46,031 --> 00:27:47,931
Ah. Mmm.

389
00:27:48,033 --> 00:27:50,934
No, I much prefer
The Invisible Man or Showboat.

390
00:27:51,036 --> 00:27:52,936
Right.
Now, shall we begin?

391
00:27:53,038 --> 00:27:56,940
Yeah. I'm, uh...
I'm ready when you are.

392
00:27:57,042 --> 00:27:59,978
- Oh, that shirt, Mr. Boone.
- Hmm?

393
00:27:59,978 --> 00:28:01,809
Oh, is new.

394
00:28:01,913 --> 00:28:05,144
Yes, I-I am sorry. Is just too white.
Is too distracting.

395
00:28:05,250 --> 00:28:08,686
W-W-Would it be asking you too much
to take it off?

396
00:28:08,820 --> 00:28:11,414
Well, I'm not wearing
an undershirt today.

397
00:28:11,556 --> 00:28:14,855
Oh, pish posh.
I'm not your Aunt Tillie. [Laughing]

398
00:28:14,959 --> 00:28:17,951
You did say that you just
wanted to draw my face, right?

399
00:28:18,063 --> 00:28:20,964
Oh, well, if is going
to make you feel uncomfortable,

400
00:28:21,066 --> 00:28:24,297
perhaps we can find
something else for you to wear.

401
00:28:26,404 --> 00:28:28,964
Now, um...

402
00:28:29,074 --> 00:28:33,909
Yes, we could drape this
across your shoulders like a toga.

403
00:28:34,012 --> 00:28:37,504
Would that help you overcome
your schoolgirl shyness?

404
00:28:37,615 --> 00:28:39,674
All right, all right.

405
00:28:39,818 --> 00:28:41,718
I'll take the shirt off.

406
00:28:43,521 --> 00:28:45,421
Kinda warm in here anyway.

407
00:28:47,992 --> 00:28:49,755
Oh, yes.
Thas better.

408
00:28:49,861 --> 00:28:51,556
Now...

409
00:28:52,897 --> 00:28:57,800
And if you'd like to sit
slightly sideways... to me.

410
00:28:57,902 --> 00:29:01,998
Thas right. And then
just put your arm on the box there.

411
00:29:03,341 --> 00:29:05,241
Just so.

412
00:29:17,622 --> 00:29:20,250
Why don't you take a picture?
lll last longer.

413
00:29:21,459 --> 00:29:24,087
Thas exactly
what I'm going to do.

414
00:29:24,195 --> 00:29:26,561
[Mutters]
Yeah.

415
00:29:26,664 --> 00:29:28,564
Mm-hmm.

416
00:29:35,306 --> 00:29:37,240
Is just like
being at the doctor.

417
00:29:37,342 --> 00:29:42,245
You have to remain perfectly still
while I examine and scrutinize you.

418
00:29:42,347 --> 00:29:45,248
[Sniffing]

419
00:29:46,584 --> 00:29:48,484
Dripping.

420
00:29:48,586 --> 00:29:50,213
Huh?

421
00:29:53,124 --> 00:29:56,025
Do you ever eat dripping
in this country?

422
00:29:57,328 --> 00:29:59,523
The fats
from roast and such...

423
00:29:59,631 --> 00:30:01,531
kept congealed in a jar...

424
00:30:01,633 --> 00:30:04,329
and then used like butter
on bread and toast.

425
00:30:04,435 --> 00:30:06,528
Sounds like something
you'd feed the dog.

426
00:30:06,638 --> 00:30:09,869
Yes, it is.
Only the poorest families ever et it.

427
00:30:09,974 --> 00:30:12,966
We used to keep ours
in a large, blue crockery jar.

428
00:30:14,078 --> 00:30:16,945
Your family ate,
uh, dripping?

429
00:30:18,550 --> 00:30:20,450
Oh, of course not.
No, no.

430
00:30:20,585 --> 00:30:22,712
As I said,
only the poorest families.

431
00:30:24,956 --> 00:30:29,086
Oh, God, is ironic.

432
00:30:29,194 --> 00:30:30,752
What is?

433
00:30:30,862 --> 00:30:35,890
I've spent much of my life
outrunning the past,

434
00:30:36,000 --> 00:30:38,901
and now it floods
all over me.

435
00:30:39,003 --> 00:30:43,667
There's something about
the openness of your face that
makes me want to tell the truth.

436
00:30:43,775 --> 00:30:47,677
Yes, our family
et dripping.

437
00:30:47,779 --> 00:30:50,179
Beef dripping.

438
00:30:50,281 --> 00:30:52,249
And four to a bed.

439
00:30:52,350 --> 00:30:55,376
And a privy out back
in the alley.

440
00:30:55,520 --> 00:30:58,580
Are you also from the slums,
Mr. Boone?

441
00:30:58,723 --> 00:31:02,489
Well, we weren't rich,
but w-w-we weren't poor either.

442
00:31:02,594 --> 00:31:04,721
No, well, you were
middle-class, hmm?

443
00:31:04,829 --> 00:31:06,729
Like all Americans,
hmm?

444
00:31:06,831 --> 00:31:12,235
Well, I don't know.
I guess you could say we lived
on the wrong side of the tracks.

445
00:31:12,337 --> 00:31:14,737
Well, in Dudley,
in the north of England,

446
00:31:14,839 --> 00:31:18,366
there were more sides to the tracks
than any American could imagine.

447
00:31:18,476 --> 00:31:20,376
Every Englishman
knows his place,

448
00:31:20,478 --> 00:31:22,878
and if you forget,
there's always someone to remind you.

449
00:31:22,981 --> 00:31:25,882
Our family had no doubt
about who they were,

450
00:31:25,984 --> 00:31:29,545
but I was an aberration
in that household, a freak of nature.

451
00:31:30,688 --> 00:31:34,089
I had imagination,
cleverness, joy.

452
00:31:34,192 --> 00:31:36,490
Now, where did I get that?

453
00:31:36,594 --> 00:31:39,085
[Chuckles]

454
00:31:39,197 --> 00:31:41,427
Certainly not from them.

455
00:31:44,202 --> 00:31:47,262
They took me out of school
when I was 14...

456
00:31:47,372 --> 00:31:50,739
and put me in a factory.

457
00:31:50,842 --> 00:31:53,743
They meant no harm.

458
00:31:53,845 --> 00:31:57,645
They were like a family of farmers
who've been given a giraffe...

459
00:31:57,749 --> 00:32:02,118
and don't know what to do
with the creature except
to harness him to the plow.

460
00:32:04,555 --> 00:32:09,083
Hatred was the only thing
that kept my soul alive...

461
00:32:09,193 --> 00:32:13,289
in that soul-killing place.

462
00:32:15,266 --> 00:32:18,827
And amongst the men
I hated...

463
00:32:18,937 --> 00:32:21,838
was my own poor,
dear, dumb father,

464
00:32:23,608 --> 00:32:27,009
who'd put me into that hell
in the first place.

465
00:32:37,322 --> 00:32:38,914
Mr. Whale?

466
00:32:40,391 --> 00:32:42,825
[Groans]

467
00:32:52,637 --> 00:32:55,197
I apologize, Mr. Boone.
l...

468
00:32:56,374 --> 00:32:58,274
Since my stroke,

469
00:32:58,376 --> 00:33:01,675
I am often overcome
with nostalgia.

470
00:33:01,779 --> 00:33:05,180
Well, I'm not that crazy about the
old man myself. You know what I mean?

471
00:33:06,985 --> 00:33:08,680
Um...

472
00:33:13,791 --> 00:33:17,090
Shall we just have a break
for five minutes, hmm?

473
00:33:17,195 --> 00:33:19,095
[Sniffs]

474
00:33:20,832 --> 00:33:22,265
[Woman] Spooky movie.
Just what this place needs tonight.

475
00:33:24,102 --> 00:33:28,004
Couldn't get any deader,
doll. Set me up.

476
00:33:28,106 --> 00:33:30,165
Your friend want one?

477
00:33:30,274 --> 00:33:33,505
Yeah. One for
whas-his-name here.

478
00:33:35,680 --> 00:33:38,046
Thanks, doll.

479
00:33:38,149 --> 00:33:40,549
I say we let lover boy
watch his movie...

480
00:33:40,685 --> 00:33:43,051
and be grateful
he's not cuttin' Shirley Temple's lawn.

481
00:33:43,154 --> 00:33:46,555
- Why is everyone
breakin' my balls tonight?
- Jesus, Boone.

482
00:33:46,657 --> 00:33:49,057
You walk in here
