If thas all right
with you.

960
01:07:25,875 --> 01:07:27,775
Nothing
would please me more.

961
01:07:30,880 --> 01:07:32,780
[Engine Starts]

962
01:07:35,551 --> 01:07:38,748
[Speaks
Scandinavian Language]

963
01:07:46,595 --> 01:07:48,495
[Whale]
Oh, good old George.

964
01:07:48,597 --> 01:07:51,191
He loves to put on the dog.

965
01:07:52,334 --> 01:07:54,234
Slim pickings.

966
01:07:54,336 --> 01:07:56,236
Mind you,
is early yet.

967
01:07:56,338 --> 01:08:00,604
Perhaps this is a good time
for us to go and pay our respects, hmm?

968
01:08:00,709 --> 01:08:02,802
Thank you.
Thank you for coming.

969
01:08:02,945 --> 01:08:05,505
Charming.
[Gasps]

970
01:08:05,648 --> 01:08:08,082
I had no idea
you'd be here.

971
01:08:08,184 --> 01:08:10,084
- How are you?
- Fine.

972
01:08:10,186 --> 01:08:12,381
I'm just fine.
And Your Royal Highness?

973
01:08:12,488 --> 01:08:15,389
Splendid, now that I know
that you're around.

974
01:08:15,491 --> 01:08:17,755
Can we get together
while I'm in town?

975
01:08:17,860 --> 01:08:21,523
- I so badly want to sit for you again.
- Sit?

976
01:08:21,630 --> 01:08:25,122
I've changed my hair, you see,
since our last session.

977
01:08:25,234 --> 01:08:28,328
Those old snaps
look rather dowdy now.

978
01:08:31,607 --> 01:08:35,600
Oh, dear.
Have I made a blunder?

979
01:08:35,744 --> 01:08:39,737
The pleasure is mine.
James Whale.

980
01:08:39,882 --> 01:08:43,841
I am such a goose.
I mistook you for Cecil Beaton.

981
01:08:43,986 --> 01:08:45,886
Is the hat.

982
01:08:45,988 --> 01:08:48,548
You're wearing
one of Cecil's hats, you know.

983
01:08:48,657 --> 01:08:51,888
George, James Whale.
David Lewis's friend.

984
01:08:51,994 --> 01:08:53,928
Oh.

985
01:08:54,029 --> 01:08:57,055
- I used to make pictures myself, ma'am.
- [Cukor] Yes, of course.

986
01:08:57,166 --> 01:08:59,566
One can't throw a rock
in this town...

987
01:08:59,668 --> 01:09:02,501
without hitting one of us
old movie directors.

988
01:09:02,605 --> 01:09:04,835
[Both Chuckling]

989
01:09:06,275 --> 01:09:10,143
Ma'am, may I introduce
Mr. Clayton Boone.

990
01:09:10,246 --> 01:09:12,771
My gardener.

991
01:09:12,915 --> 01:09:15,941
- How do you do? Clay... Clay Boone.
- Quite.

992
01:09:16,085 --> 01:09:19,714
- I adore gardens.
- [All Chuckling]

993
01:09:19,822 --> 01:09:22,620
He's never met
a princess.

994
01:09:22,725 --> 01:09:24,625
Only queens.

995
01:09:28,831 --> 01:09:31,732
Well, George, ma'am,
this has been an honor,

996
01:09:31,834 --> 01:09:35,463
and one that I shall remember
for the rest of my life.

997
01:09:45,314 --> 01:09:46,781
Great place.

998
01:09:46,916 --> 01:09:49,350
Mmm.
[Chuckles]

999
01:09:49,451 --> 01:09:51,351
Hello.

1000
01:09:55,457 --> 01:09:58,858
- What was that all about?
- Oh, don't worry.
Nothing of any importance.

1001
01:09:58,961 --> 01:10:02,362
Just two old men
slapping each other with lilies.

1002
01:10:02,464 --> 01:10:05,695
- I'm sorry.
- [Woman Laughs]

1003
01:10:05,801 --> 01:10:08,395
- Who's that?
- David.

1004
01:10:08,504 --> 01:10:12,201
- The friend I thought was in New York.
- No, l-l... The girl.

1005
01:10:12,308 --> 01:10:15,141
- Oh, is Elizabeth Taylor.
- Oh, thank you.

1006
01:10:18,447 --> 01:10:21,348
Yes, David produced
her last picture.

1007
01:10:21,450 --> 01:10:24,851
- What are you doing here?
- I was just going to ask you
the same thing.

1008
01:10:24,954 --> 01:10:27,354
Thought you were
still in New York.

1009
01:10:27,456 --> 01:10:29,947
I was,
until last night.

1010
01:10:30,059 --> 01:10:31,959
I was going to call.

1011
01:10:32,061 --> 01:10:33,961
- David Lewis.
- Hey. Clay Boone.

1012
01:10:34,063 --> 01:10:38,466
Our yardman, who's been kind enough
to serve as my escort...

1013
01:10:38,567 --> 01:10:40,467
to George's little do.

1014
01:10:42,571 --> 01:10:44,971
Should you be drinking
in your condition?

1015
01:10:45,074 --> 01:10:48,475
Oh, David, will you
stop being a nanny.

1016
01:10:48,611 --> 01:10:51,512
I think I'm gonna
go and get another beer.

1017
01:10:53,916 --> 01:10:55,816
[Giggles]

1018
01:10:55,918 --> 01:10:59,149
You shoulïve seen George's face
when he saw Clayton.

1019
01:10:59,255 --> 01:11:01,086
Oh!
[Giggles]

1020
01:11:01,190 --> 01:11:04,091
- You didn't, Jimmy.
- I did.

1021
01:11:04,193 --> 01:11:08,220
Mind you, Princess Margares
an absolute doll.

1022
01:11:08,330 --> 01:11:12,892
Well, we're all equals in her eyes,
as commoners, I presume.

1023
01:11:13,002 --> 01:11:14,902
You only
embarrass yourself.

1024
01:11:15,004 --> 01:11:18,906
- Oh, dear. I'll never
work in this town again.
- You know what I mean.

1025
01:11:19,008 --> 01:11:22,910
- Your reputation.
- I have no reputation.

1026
01:11:23,045 --> 01:11:25,946
I'm as free as the air.

1027
01:11:26,048 --> 01:11:28,573
But the rest of us
aren't.

1028
01:11:28,717 --> 01:11:30,685
- Can't you remember that?
- No.

1029
01:11:30,819 --> 01:11:33,379
I never could.

1030
01:11:33,489 --> 01:11:36,890
I suppose you regret
having got me invited here.

1031
01:11:38,327 --> 01:11:40,818
I didn't ask George
to invite you.

1032
01:11:40,929 --> 01:11:43,329
Oh.
Well, then, who did?

1033
01:11:43,432 --> 01:11:46,333
I have people here
I need to speak to.

1034
01:11:46,435 --> 01:11:50,337
- You'll be all right on your own?
- Yes, yes, perfectly.

1035
01:11:50,439 --> 01:11:53,340
I'll drop by tomorrow
for breakfast.

1036
01:11:53,442 --> 01:11:55,342
Oh, yes.

1037
01:11:58,347 --> 01:12:00,679
Oh.

1038
01:12:00,783 --> 01:12:02,683
Oh, I say.

1039
01:12:02,785 --> 01:12:04,685
Thank you very much.

1040
01:12:04,787 --> 01:12:06,687
Just the one.

1041
01:12:26,442 --> 01:12:28,342
[Sighs]

1042
01:12:42,057 --> 01:12:45,288
Mr. Whale!
Mr. Whale!

1043
01:12:46,829 --> 01:12:48,922
[High-Pitched Giggle]

1044
01:12:49,031 --> 01:12:52,398
- Mr. Whale.
- Mr. Kay.

1045
01:12:52,501 --> 01:12:55,902
Bet you never thought
you'd see me again. [Laughs]

1046
01:12:56,004 --> 01:12:59,405
- I didn't know if you'd be well
enough to come to this party.
- You didn't?

1047
01:12:59,508 --> 01:13:03,638
I'm the one who got you
on Mr. Cukor's guest list.

1048
01:13:03,779 --> 01:13:06,680
You, Mr. Kay?

1049
01:13:06,782 --> 01:13:09,376
But how do you know
George Cukor?

1050
01:13:09,485 --> 01:13:11,817
I interviewed him
after I met you.

1051
01:13:11,920 --> 01:13:13,820
I'm his
social secretary now.

1052
01:13:13,922 --> 01:13:17,221
Well, assistant
to his secretary.

1053
01:13:17,326 --> 01:13:18,987
Yes, I commend you.

1054
01:13:19,094 --> 01:13:21,028
If you're going to
pursue poofs,

1055
01:13:21,130 --> 01:13:23,997
go after those
who can do favors for you.

1056
01:13:24,099 --> 01:13:28,661
You just waste everyone's time
when you court dinosaurs.

1057
01:13:28,771 --> 01:13:31,171
Don't think like that,
Mr. Whale.

1058
01:13:31,273 --> 01:13:33,173
I love your movies.

1059
01:13:33,275 --> 01:13:36,904
Thas why I wanted you to come...
so I could see you with your monsters.

1060
01:13:37,045 --> 01:13:38,740
My monsters?

1061
01:13:38,881 --> 01:13:41,315
Don't go away.
[Giggles]

1062
01:13:44,353 --> 01:13:47,618
- Uh, excuse me. Miss Lanchester, l...
- Yes?

1063
01:13:48,724 --> 01:13:50,783
[Whispers]
Elsa.

1064
01:14:02,004 --> 01:14:03,904
Jimmy!

1065
01:14:05,140 --> 01:14:07,040
Elsa.

1066
01:14:07,142 --> 01:14:09,633
- How are you?
- Mmm.

1067
01:14:11,547 --> 01:14:13,447
[Giggles]

1068
01:14:13,549 --> 01:14:16,450
I saw Una O'Connor
a few weeks ago.

1069
01:14:16,552 --> 01:14:19,385
She said you'd been
under the weather.

1070
01:14:19,488 --> 01:14:22,480
Oh, well, nothing
out of the ordinary. Getting old.

1071
01:14:22,591 --> 01:14:25,992
Nonsense! Ah,
whas our pesky friend up to now?

1072
01:14:26,094 --> 01:14:27,994
Mmm?

1073
01:14:28,096 --> 01:14:31,088
- [Elsa] Is that Boris?
- [Whale Sighs]

1074
01:14:31,200 --> 01:14:35,227
- Our little chum appears
to be arranging a reunion.
- Oh, dear.

1075
01:14:35,337 --> 01:14:38,431
- Boris, darling.
- Elsa. Elsa!

1076
01:14:38,540 --> 01:14:42,203
And James.
James.

1077
01:14:42,344 --> 01:14:45,336
- How good to see you.
- I didn't know you were here.

1078
01:14:45,481 --> 01:14:48,382
These public revels
are hardly up your alley.

1079
01:14:48,484 --> 01:14:52,648
Actually, I'm here
for the sake of Miranda,

1080
01:14:52,754 --> 01:14:55,018
my great-grandniece.

1081
01:14:55,123 --> 01:14:56,954
- Koochie-koo. [Chuckles]
- [Baby Coos]

1082
01:14:57,059 --> 01:14:59,857
And what do you make
of our royal visitant?

1083
01:14:59,962 --> 01:15:02,931
Perfectly charming.
A real lady.

1084
01:15:03,031 --> 01:15:06,660
- What did you expect,
a hussy in tennis shoes?
- [Laughs]

1085
01:15:06,768 --> 01:15:09,931
Hey, you, with the camera.
We got a historical moment here.

1086
01:15:10,038 --> 01:15:11,938
Come,
get a picture of it.

1087
01:15:12,040 --> 01:15:16,477
This is Mr. James Whale, who made
Frankenstein and Bride of Frankenstein,

1088
01:15:16,578 --> 01:15:20,912
and this... forget the baby a second...
is the Monster...

1089
01:15:21,016 --> 01:15:23,143
and his bride.

1090
01:15:23,252 --> 01:15:26,050
Oh, Karloff.
Right.

1091
01:15:29,858 --> 01:15:32,759
Don't you just love
being famous?

1092
01:15:35,697 --> 01:15:39,360
[Dr. Pretorius] To a new world
of gods and monsters.

1093
01:15:39,468 --> 01:15:43,268
[Gunfire,
Explosions Continue]

1094
01:15:51,613 --> 01:15:54,810
- Are you all right, Jimmy?
- Yeah. Yeah.

1095
01:15:55,617 --> 01:15:57,517
Got it.

1096
01:16:04,860 --> 01:16:06,760
[Clay]
Mr. Whale.

1097
01:16:09,498 --> 01:16:12,399
- Are you okay?
- I'm tired. I'm a bit tired.

1098
01:16:13,702 --> 01:16:15,932
Are you
enjoying yourself?

1099
01:16:16,038 --> 01:16:19,872
No. Actually, l... I feel
a little out of place here.

1100
01:16:19,975 --> 01:16:23,433
Well, neither of us
really fits in here.

1101
01:16:24,980 --> 01:16:28,006
That musve been funny for you,
seeing your monsters again.

1102
01:16:28,116 --> 01:16:31,176
Monsters?
The only monsters are here.

1103
01:16:31,286 --> 01:16:33,686
[Thunder Crashes]

1104
01:16:33,789 --> 01:16:35,689
[Guests Chattering,
Screaming]

1105
01:16:35,791 --> 01:16:38,089
Oh, fuck.
We left the top down.

1106
01:16:38,226 --> 01:16:40,990
- You wanna run for it?
- [Whale] "Run for it"?

1107
01:16:41,096 --> 01:16:42,996
Is raining.

1108
01:16:43,098 --> 01:16:46,192
- [Woman] Hurry! Hurry!
- Whoo!

1109
01:16:46,301 --> 01:16:48,496
[Hooting, Laughing]

1110
01:17:08,924 --> 01:17:10,858
Mr. Whale?

1111
01:17:12,461 --> 01:17:14,361
Mr. Whale.

1112
01:17:15,464 --> 01:17:18,297
Les get out
of this fuckhole.

1113
01:17:18,400 --> 01:17:21,301
You sure you don't
want to wait it out?

1114
01:17:21,403 --> 01:17:24,304
We aren't made of sugar.
We won't melt.

1115
01:17:24,406 --> 01:17:26,306
[Thunder Rumbling]

1116
01:17:26,408 --> 01:17:30,208
"Oh, that this too,
too solid flesh would melt."

1117
01:17:30,312 --> 01:17:34,214
I'm getting you home before you
catch your death of pneumonia.

1118
01:17:34,316 --> 01:17:36,546
Catch my death?

1119
01:17:36,652 --> 01:17:38,552
Are you okay,
Mr. Whale?

1120
01:17:39,988 --> 01:17:43,549
Jimmy, please, hmm?

1121
01:17:43,692 --> 01:17:45,592
Call me Jimmy.

1122
01:17:45,694 --> 01:17:48,094
[Engine Starts,
Revs]

1123
01:17:52,868 --> 01:17:54,927
- [Thunder Continues]
- Hanna, we need some towels!
We're soaked to the bone!

1124
01:17:57,039 --> 01:17:58,939
Oh, blast it.

1125
01:17:59,041 --> 01:18:02,875
Well, if we soil your floors,
is your own bloody fault!

1126
01:18:08,150 --> 01:18:10,050
Oh, I don't believe it.

1127
01:18:10,152 --> 01:18:13,713
Don't worry, she'll be back.
She just can't say "no" to her daughter.

1128
01:18:13,822 --> 01:18:17,121
Well, you certainly have better things
to do than to baby-sit an old man.

1129
01:18:17,259 --> 01:18:20,160
I didn't have anything
planned.

1130
01:18:20,262 --> 01:18:25,063
Well, go get a shower upstairs
and I'll get you something dry to wear.

1131
01:18:26,168 --> 01:18:28,568
[Thunder Continues]

1132
01:18:32,541 --> 01:18:36,238
Well, what do you think?
Hmm?

1133
01:18:36,344 --> 01:18:38,244
Mr. Whale?

1134
01:18:42,918 --> 01:18:46,081
Where are those clothes
you promised?

1135
01:18:46,188 --> 01:18:48,088
[Clay]
Mr. Whale?

1136
01:18:48,190 --> 01:18:50,090
He trusts me,
you know.

1137
01:18:55,597 --> 01:18:57,497
Mr. Whale?

1138
01:18:59,601 --> 01:19:01,432
Jimmy?

1139
01:19:05,574 --> 01:19:07,701
Oh, yes.

1140
01:19:07,809 --> 01:19:09,709
- Mr. Whale?
- Huh?

1141
01:19:13,749 --> 01:19:15,478
Yes, of course,
uh, Clayton.

1142
01:19:15,584 --> 01:19:18,917
Do come in. Now, I promised to
get you some dry clothes.

1143
01:19:19,020 --> 01:19:22,649
The trouble is, you're so large.
You wouldn't want to attempt
to get into my pants.

1144
01:19:22,791 --> 01:19:26,056
- Uh, n-no. Definitely not.
- Very good, Clayton.

1145
01:19:26,194 --> 01:19:28,424
Now...
Oh, I know!

1146
01:19:28,530 --> 01:19:31,328
This... This absolutely
swims on me,

1147
01:19:31,433 --> 01:19:35,267
so that should deal
with your upper half.

1148
01:19:35,370 --> 01:19:38,828
And now we just need to deal
with the rest, don't we?

1149
01:19:38,940 --> 01:19:41,841
- Do you have any baggy shorts
or pajama bottoms?
- Uh, no.

1150
01:19:41,943 --> 01:19:44,844
I'm sorry. Uh, my pajamas
are all tailored.

1151
01:19:44,946 --> 01:19:47,847
Would it be too distressing
for you to continue with that towel?

1152
01:19:47,949 --> 01:19:50,850
Is hardly more immodest
than a kilt, you know.

1153
01:19:50,952 --> 01:19:53,079
Yes?
How very sporting of you, Clayton.

1154
01:19:53,188 --> 01:19:55,588
Say, is this, um, the...

1155
01:19:55,690 --> 01:19:59,592
Yes, is the only memento
I ever kept.

1156
01:19:59,694 --> 01:20:02,162
My original sketch
for the Monster.

1157
01:20:02,297 --> 01:20:04,731
- Uh, shall we?
- Yeah.

1158
01:20:14,709 --> 01:20:17,109
[Thunder Continues]

1159
01:20:17,212 --> 01:20:20,875
When we've finished eating,
if Hanna's not back, shall we
try a few more sketches?

1160
01:20:20,982 --> 01:20:23,883
I thought you'd given up
on my drawing.

1161
01:20:23,985 --> 01:20:25,885
Yeah, but I'd like
to try again.

1162
01:20:25,987 --> 01:20:29,286
Ill give us something to do
while we wait.

1163
01:20:32,194 --> 01:20:34,754
Tell me something,
Clayton.

1164
01:20:36,231 --> 01:20:38,461
Do you believe
in mercy killing?

1165
01:20:40,135 --> 01:20:42,228
I never really gave it
much thought.

1166
01:20:42,337 --> 01:20:45,465
You musve come across
such situations in Korea.

1167
01:20:45,574 --> 01:20:48,975
A wounded comrade,
or perhaps even an enemy.

1168
01:20:49,077 --> 01:20:52,808
You know, someone for whom death
would be a blessing.

1169
01:20:54,616 --> 01:20:56,516
I never went to Korea.

1170
01:20:56,618 --> 01:20:59,519
I never even made it
through boot camp.

1171
01:20:59,621 --> 01:21:03,682
- But you said...
- That I was a marine, which is true.

1172
01:21:03,825 --> 01:21:05,725
You filled in the rest.

1173
01:21:08,396 --> 01:21:10,296
Oh, I see.

1174
01:21:12,734 --> 01:21:15,294
My old man was a marine.

1175
01:21:15,403 --> 01:21:17,303
Lied about his age,
and he enlisted.

1176
01:21:17,405 --> 01:21:20,306
- Is this the Great War?
- Yeah. Yeah.

1177
01:21:20,408 --> 01:21:23,809
By the time he was ready to ship out,
all the fighting was over,

1178
01:21:23,912 --> 01:21:26,813
so he felt like
he'd missed out.

1179
01:21:26,915 --> 01:21:30,510
- Well, it was
a very lucky thing he did.
- Thas not the way he saw it.

1180
01:21:30,619 --> 01:21:34,248
To him it was like his life
never really got started.

1181
01:21:34,356 --> 01:21:37,416
Nothing else
seemed to matter.

1182
01:21:37,559 --> 01:21:39,493
Certainly not his family.

1183
01:21:39,628 --> 01:21:43,189
Is that why you became a marine,
for your father's sake?

1184
01:21:43,331 --> 01:21:46,232
I figured id be
the next best thing.

1185
01:21:46,334 --> 01:21:49,235
I mean, but I loved it too.
I really... I did.

1186
01:21:49,337 --> 01:21:52,738
It was a chance to be
a part of something important,

1187
01:21:52,841 --> 01:21:54,741
something thas bigger
than yourself.

1188
01:21:54,843 --> 01:21:56,868
So, what happened?

1189
01:21:56,978 --> 01:21:59,708
Didn't have the guts for it.

1190
01:21:59,814 --> 01:22:01,907
- Hmm?
- Literally.

1191
01:22:03,518 --> 01:22:05,577
My appendix burst.

1192
01:22:06,821 --> 01:22:09,119
They gave me
a medical discharge.

1193
01:22:09,257 --> 01:22:12,488
The only thing I can think is,
how the hell am I gonna tell my father?

1194
01:22:16,131 --> 01:22:19,328
And you know what happened
when I finally did tell him?

1195
01:22:21,403 --> 01:22:23,633
He laughed at me.

1196
01:22:32,280 --> 01:22:34,407
Well, them's the breaks,
huh? So...

1197
01:22:34,516 --> 01:22:36,416
No war stories for this pup.

1198
01:22:41,389 --> 01:22:43,289
Thas where you're wrong,
Clayton.

1199
01:22:45,927 --> 01:22:47,986
You just told me one.

1200
01:22:48,129 --> 01:22:50,529
A very good story indeed.

1201
01:22:52,133 --> 01:22:54,033
- [Thunder Continues]
- Whew.

1202
01:22:54,135 --> 01:22:56,103
This storm
is getting worse.

1203
01:22:56,204 --> 01:23:00,140
"A perfect night
for mystery and horror.

1204
01:23:01,409 --> 01:23:04,810
The air itself
is filled with monsters."

1205
01:23:04,913 --> 01:23:08,508
- Thas from one of your movies, right?
- Very good.

1206
01:23:08,616 --> 01:23:11,720
"The only monsters
are here."

1207
01:23:11,720 --> 01:23:13,654
Don't remember that one.

1208
01:23:13,755 --> 01:23:15,655
James Whale.

1209
01:23:15,757 --> 01:23:19,090
This afternoon at the party when
you said, "The only monsters are here,"

1210
01:23:19,194 --> 01:23:21,754
I was wondering
which "here" that was.

1211
01:23:21,863 --> 01:23:23,763
No, I d... I don't recall.

1212
01:23:25,867 --> 01:23:29,064
Memories of the war,
perhaps.

1213
01:23:34,175 --> 01:23:36,075
Barnett.

1214
01:23:38,179 --> 01:23:40,272
Barnett on the wire.

1215
01:23:40,382 --> 01:23:42,316
Your friend.

1216
01:23:42,417 --> 01:23:44,317
Yes.

1217
01:23:44,452 --> 01:23:48,354
He caught his one night
coming back from reconnaissance.

1218
01:23:48,456 --> 01:23:51,357
I wouldn't take him,
but McGill did,

1219
01:23:51,459 --> 01:23:55,020
"just to give the laddie
a taste."

1220
01:23:55,130 --> 01:23:59,032
They were nearly home
when a Maxim gun opened fire.

1221
01:24:03,471 --> 01:24:07,373
Barnes body landed on this wire
that was as thick as briers.

1222
01:24:07,475 --> 01:24:09,875
It was hanging there
the next morning.

1223
01:24:09,978 --> 01:24:12,879
It was only a hundred yards
from the line,

1224
01:24:12,981 --> 01:24:16,883
but too far...
for anyone to fetch it.

1225
01:24:19,954 --> 01:24:23,685
So we saw him every morning stand-to
and every evening stand-to.

1226
01:24:23,792 --> 01:24:28,024
"Good morning, Barnett,"
we used to say to him.

1227
01:24:28,129 --> 01:24:33,726
"How's Barnett looking today?"
"He seemed a little peaked.
Looks a little plumper."

1228
01:24:34,836 --> 01:24:38,135
And he hung there...
[Exhales]

1229
01:24:38,239 --> 01:24:41,140
well, at least
until we were relieved.

1230
01:24:41,242 --> 01:24:44,336
We introduced him to the new unit
before marching out,

1231
01:24:44,446 --> 01:24:47,347
speaking highly
of his companionship.

1232
01:24:49,651 --> 01:24:53,712
God, we were a witty lot.

1233
01:24:53,855 --> 01:24:56,050
Laughing at our dead,

1234
01:24:56,157 --> 01:24:58,557
feeling that
it was our death too.

1235
01:24:58,660 --> 01:25:02,323
But I tell you,
for each man who died I thought,

1236
01:25:02,430 --> 01:25:05,331
"Better you than me,
poor sod."

1237
01:25:08,203 --> 01:25:12,037
You know, a whole generation
was wiped out by that war.

1238
01:25:12,140 --> 01:25:14,540
- [Thunder Continues]
- You survived it.

1239
01:25:14,642 --> 01:25:16,803
Can't hurt you now.

1240
01:25:16,911 --> 01:25:18,742
No good to dig it up.

1241
01:25:18,847 --> 01:25:21,247
Oh.

1242
01:25:21,349 --> 01:25:23,408
Friend,
is digging itself up.

1243
01:25:23,551 --> 01:25:27,453
There is nothing in the here and now
to take my mind off it.

1244
01:25:28,623 --> 01:25:31,854
The parties...
Well, you were there.

1245
01:25:33,027 --> 01:25:37,521
Reading... I can't...
I-I can't concentrate.

1246
01:25:37,632 --> 01:25:39,532
There's no work, of course,

1247
01:25:39,634 --> 01:25:43,536
and, uh, love
and, uh, painting and, uh...

1248
01:25:48,309 --> 01:25:50,368
Drawing, I mean.

1249
01:25:53,815 --> 01:25:55,715
Look.

1250
01:25:58,920 --> 01:26:01,252
Your portrait, Clayton.

1251
01:26:04,893 --> 01:26:07,794
Is all gone for me now.
All gone.

1252
01:26:10,798 --> 01:26:13,699
They're nothing but
the scribblings of an infant.

1253
01:26:14,969 --> 01:26:16,869
There's nothing.

1254
01:26:16,971 --> 01:26:18,700
Nothing.

1255
01:26:46,801 --> 01:26:49,702
You said you wanted
to draw me like a statue.

1256
01:26:54,475 --> 01:26:55,874
Okay.

1257
01:27:18,967 --> 01:27:21,868
Is going to happen
after all.

1258
01:27:21,970 --> 01:27:23,961
What did you say?

1259
01:27:25,573 --> 01:27:27,768
No, it won't do.

1260
01:27:27,875 --> 01:27:31,675
- What won't do?
- You're much too human.

1261
01:27:31,779 --> 01:27:34,304
Well, what do you expect,
bronze?

1262
01:27:36,417 --> 01:27:38,044
Don't move.

1263
01:27:44,092 --> 01:27:46,492
[Grunting Noise]

1264
01:27:52,867 --> 01:27:56,166
- I want you to wear this.
- Why?

1265
01:27:56,271 --> 01:27:58,171
So I can see
the artistic effect.

1266
01:27:58,273 --> 01:28:01,265
Your very human body
against the inhuman mask.

1267
01:28:01,376 --> 01:28:03,867
- Oh! Very striking. Mmm.
- I don't know.

1268
01:28:03,978 --> 01:28:07,072
Oh, come on, Clayton. Just for a minute,
so I can see the effects.

1269
01:28:07,181 --> 01:28:10,116
- From the first World War, isn't it?
- Mmm, yes.

1270
01:28:10,218 --> 01:28:13,619
Fasten this around the back.
Let me help you.

1271
01:28:13,721 --> 01:28:15,552
There.

1272
01:28:15,657 --> 01:28:17,488
Hmm?

1273
01:28:18,593 --> 01:28:21,061
[Sniffing, Gasping]

1274
01:28:21,195 --> 01:28:23,925
Uh...

1275
01:28:24,032 --> 01:28:25,522
now what?

1276
01:28:25,633 --> 01:28:27,760
All right,
les take it off.

1277
01:28:27,869 --> 01:28:30,030
Uh, is too tight.
I can't breathe.

1278
01:28:30,138 --> 01:28:33,198
Oh, no, l-l-leave it.
I'll help.

1279
01:28:33,308 --> 01:28:35,208
Leave it to me.

1280
01:28:39,747 --> 01:28:41,806
Wha... Can you...

1281
01:28:41,916 --> 01:28:43,816
I'm still here.

1282
01:28:43,918 --> 01:28:45,852
All right.

1283
01:28:47,322 --> 01:28:49,222
Mr. Whale.

1284
01:28:49,324 --> 01:28:52,885
- [Panicked Breathing]
- Oh, what steely muscles
you've got there.

1285
01:28:52,994 --> 01:28:55,895
Just take the fuckin' mask
off me now, okay?

1286
01:28:55,997 --> 01:28:58,932
- What a solid brute you are.
- Hey... Oh...

1287
01:28:59,033 --> 01:29:01,593
Hey... Hey, just get
your fuckin' hands off me!

1288
01:29:01,703 --> 01:29:06,072
Is no use, Clayton.
I can't hear you. I can't hear a word.

1289
01:29:06,174 --> 01:29:08,836
Oh, well, then,
maybe this.

1290
01:29:08,943 --> 01:29:11,070
- Hey, hey, hey, hey!
- [Whale Groans]

1291
01:29:12,613 --> 01:29:15,309
- Ohh!
- Yes!

1292
01:29:15,416 --> 01:29:18,783
- Now I've got you! How will
you ever get yourself back?
- Get off me!

1293
01:29:18,920 --> 01:29:22,822
I told you, I'm not that way! Get it
through your fuckin' head, all right?

1294
01:29:23,925 --> 01:29:26,052
You feel so good,
Clayton.

1295
01:29:27,395 --> 01:29:29,022
[Groans]

1296
01:29:29,130 --> 01:29:31,394
Didn't even sting!

1297
01:29:31,499 --> 01:29:33,660
- [Grunting, Laughing]
- [Groans]

1298
01:29:33,768 --> 01:29:36,999
Wait till I tell my friends about this.
Won't they be surprised.

1299
01:29:37,105 --> 01:29:40,006
I haven't done anything
with you... [Gasps]

1300
01:29:40,108 --> 01:29:43,805
You undressed for me. I've been
kissing you. I even touched your prick!

1301
01:29:43,911 --> 01:29:47,108
- How will you ever be able
to live with yourself?
- What do you want from me?

1302
01:29:47,215 --> 01:29:50,810
[Laughing Hysterically]
I want you to kill me.

1303
01:29:50,918 --> 01:29:52,146
What?

1304
01:29:52,286 --> 01:29:54,186
Break my neck.

1305
01:29:54,288 --> 01:29:57,223
Come on, strangle me. Ill be so easy
to choke the life out of me.

1306
01:29:57,325 --> 01:29:59,350
Oh, God.

1307
01:29:59,494 --> 01:30:01,928
We've come this far.

1308
01:30:02,029 --> 01:30:03,519
I'm losing my mind.

1309
01:30:03,631 --> 01:30:07,123
Every day a new piece of it goes,
and soon there'll be none of it left.

1310
01:30:07,235 --> 01:30:10,727
But if you kill me,

1311
01:30:10,838 --> 01:30:12,738
death will be bearable.

1312
01:30:14,542 --> 01:30:16,806
You could be
my second monster.

1313
01:30:16,911 --> 01:30:20,540
Come on.
Please, do it now.

1314
01:30:20,648 --> 01:30:22,548
Make me invisible.

1315
01:30:22,650 --> 01:30:25,551
[Panting, Groaning]

1316
01:30:27,822 --> 01:30:29,084
I am not...

1317
01:30:30,691 --> 01:30:32,215
your monster!

1318
01:30:35,663 --> 01:30:38,564
[Sobbing]

1319
01:30:44,172 --> 01:30:45,901
[Grunts]

1320
01:30:47,008 --> 01:30:49,408
[Sobbing Continues]

1321
01:30:52,313 --> 01:30:54,713
You're
a bloody pussycat.

1322
01:31:08,663 --> 01:31:11,894
My deepest apologies.

1323
01:31:11,999 --> 01:31:14,433
Can you ever forgive me?

1324
01:31:16,070 --> 01:31:18,470
No, I suppose not.

1325
01:31:23,644 --> 01:31:29,514
[Protracted Sigh]

1326
01:31:37,258 --> 01:31:39,658
I've got to go to bed.

1327
01:31:51,472 --> 01:31:53,372
Are you okay?

1328
01:31:53,508 --> 01:31:55,408
Oh, Clayton.

1329
01:31:55,510 --> 01:31:57,068
Do you need some help?

1330
01:31:58,212 --> 01:32:00,578
Pray you undo this button.

1331
01:32:05,419 --> 01:32:08,820
I don't seem to be able to manage it
when I'm tired.

1332
01:32:11,092 --> 01:32:15,495
Do you believe people
come into our lives for a purpose?

1333
01:32:19,867 --> 01:32:21,767
Okay, I can manage now.

1334
01:32:25,673 --> 01:32:27,607
[Groans]
Oh.

1335
01:32:27,708 --> 01:32:32,611
When you die, make sure that your brain
is the last organ to fizzle.

1336
01:32:32,713 --> 01:32:35,079
[Sighs]

1337
01:32:35,182 --> 01:32:37,275
You'll feel better tomorrow.

1338
01:32:39,854 --> 01:32:41,754
[Grunts]

1339
01:32:46,794 --> 01:32:48,694
[Moans]

1340
01:32:48,796 --> 01:32:50,696
Good night.

1341
01:32:52,433 --> 01:32:54,901
Good night.

1342
01:32:55,002 --> 01:32:56,902
[Sighs]

1343
01:33:08,416 --> 01:33:12,318
[Thunder Continues]

1344
01:33:14,255 --> 01:33:16,985
[Gunfire,
Bomb Whistling]

1345
01:33:17,091 --> 01:33:20,492
[Explosions,
Gunfire Continues]

1346
01:34:26,527 --> 01:34:28,461
[Telephone Rings]

1347
01:34:28,629 --> 01:34:30,460
[Snorts, Gasps]

1348
01:34:32,733 --> 01:34:35,361
- [Ringing Continues]
- [Hanna] Hello?

1349
01:34:35,469 --> 01:34:37,699
Oh, hello,
Mr. David.

1350
01:34:37,805 --> 01:34:41,741
No, he did not tell me, but
thas no problem. I make the breakfast.

1351
01:34:41,842 --> 01:34:44,402
10:00. Yes, very good.
Good-bye.

1352
01:34:44,545 --> 01:34:47,776
[Groans] Hanna, this is not
what you think it is.

1353
01:34:47,882 --> 01:34:49,782
- [Shoes Land On Floor]
- Aah!

1354
01:34:49,884 --> 01:34:52,785
I brought you your clothes. Get dressed
and go. We have guest for breakfast.

1355
01:34:52,887 --> 01:34:55,287
I need to talk to you
about Mr. Whale.

1356
01:34:55,389 --> 01:34:57,789
Nothing you could say
would surprise me.

1357
01:34:57,892 --> 01:35:01,225
Maybe, but I still need to talk to you
about him. Let me have a cup of coffee.

1358
01:35:01,328 --> 01:35:04,729
[Scoffs] I blame my daughter
for keeping me out so late.

1359
01:35:04,832 --> 01:35:07,733
I only hope you did not
get him excited.

1360
01:35:07,835 --> 01:35:10,235
You could give him
new stroke.

1361
01:35:10,337 --> 01:35:12,737
- Why do you do it, Hanna?
- What I do?

1362
01:35:12,840 --> 01:35:16,276
Why do you take care of him
like he was your own flesh and blood?

1363
01:35:16,377 --> 01:35:20,211
Is my job.
I did it when he was happy; it was easy.

1364
01:35:20,314 --> 01:35:23,215
Is only fair I do it
now he is ill.

1365
01:35:23,317 --> 01:35:26,718
Oh, enough of this talk.
I must go wake the master.

1366
01:35:32,526 --> 01:35:35,256
Mr. Jimmy,
good morning.

1367
01:35:35,362 --> 01:35:37,262
Mr. Jimmy?

1368
01:35:41,669 --> 01:35:43,569
What have you done
with him?

1369
01:35:43,671 --> 01:35:46,572
- You look for him.
- I put him to bed last night.

1370
01:35:46,707 --> 01:35:49,733
Mr. Jimmy?
Mr. Jimmy!

1371
01:36:24,845 --> 01:36:26,904
Mr. Jimmy!

1372
01:36:27,047 --> 01:36:29,948
- [Grunting]
- Oh! Mr. Jimmy!

1373
01:36:31,051 --> 01:36:32,951
Mr. Jimmy!

1374
01:36:33,053 --> 01:36:34,953
You son of a bitch!

1375
01:36:35,055 --> 01:36:38,183
Oh!
No! No! No!

1376
01:36:38,292 --> 01:36:42,490
Mr. Jimmy! Jimmy!
Jimmy!

1377
01:36:42,596 --> 01:36:46,362
H-He wanted me to kill him,
and then he did it himself!

1378
01:36:46,467 --> 01:36:48,025
I didn't do this!

1379
01:36:48,135 --> 01:36:50,228
Mr. Jimmy.

1380
01:36:50,337 --> 01:36:52,396
Ohh.

1381
01:36:52,506 --> 01:36:54,531
l-lt says here,
"Good-bye."

1382
01:36:54,675 --> 01:36:56,575
I find in his room.

1383
01:36:56,677 --> 01:37:00,169
Sorry, he says.
He's had wonderful life.

1384
01:37:00,314 --> 01:37:02,305
Oh, my Mr. Jimmy.

1385
01:37:02,449 --> 01:37:04,349
Poor, foolish man.

1386
01:37:04,451 --> 01:37:06,578
[Moaning]

1387
01:37:08,522 --> 01:37:14,085
You could not wait for God
to take you in His time?

1388
01:37:15,863 --> 01:37:18,764
You must leave.
You were not here this morning.

1389
01:37:18,866 --> 01:37:21,198
Look, I did not do this.

1390
01:37:21,302 --> 01:37:24,465
- Police will not know that.
They will want to investigate.
- W-We got a note.

1391
01:37:24,572 --> 01:37:27,063
You want them to question you
about Mr. Jimmy?

1392
01:37:27,208 --> 01:37:30,143
Please, Clayton, is better
that I find the body alone.

1393
01:37:30,277 --> 01:37:33,178
How are you gonna explain
how you got him out of the water?

1394
01:37:33,280 --> 01:37:35,680
[Muttering
In Scandinavian Language]

1395
01:37:35,783 --> 01:37:38,183
You're right.
[Sniffles]

1396
01:37:38,285 --> 01:37:40,378
Uh, we must put him back.

1397
01:37:40,487 --> 01:37:42,318
W... Uh...
[Sighs]

1398
01:37:42,423 --> 01:37:46,325
Oh, Mr. Jimmy,
we do not mean disrespect.

1399
01:37:46,427 --> 01:37:49,726
- You will keep better in water.
- God.

1400
01:37:49,830 --> 01:37:52,196
[Grunting, Groaning]

1401
01:37:52,299 --> 01:37:54,665
[Muttering
In Scandinavian Language]

1402
01:38:03,143 --> 01:38:07,045
?? [Violin]

1403
01:38:28,802 --> 01:38:31,032
?? [Continues]

1404
01:38:31,138 --> 01:38:33,038
[Moans]

1405
01:38:36,510 --> 01:38:38,410
[Moans]

1406
01:38:41,181 --> 01:38:42,705
[Growls]

1407
01:38:44,585 --> 01:38:46,485
[Moaning]

1408
01:38:46,587 --> 01:38:48,748
Who are you?

1409
01:38:50,090 --> 01:38:53,992
I think
you're a stranger to me.

1410
01:38:54,094 --> 01:38:58,394
I cannot see you.
I cannot see anything.

1411
01:38:58,499 --> 01:39:02,367
You must please excuse me,
but I'm blind.

1412
01:39:02,469 --> 01:39:03,604
- [Moans]
- [Blind Man]
Perhaps you're afflicted too.

1413
01:39:03,604 --> 01:39:06,937
- [Moans]
- [Blind Man]
Perhaps you're afflicted too.

1414
01:39:07,041 --> 01:39:10,033
We shall be friends.

1415
01:39:10,144 --> 01:39:12,044
Is very lonely here,

1416
01:39:12,146 --> 01:39:16,173
and is been a long time since
any human being came into this hut.

1417
01:39:16,283 --> 01:39:19,912
I'll look after you,

1418
01:39:20,020 --> 01:39:22,955
and you
will comfort me.

1419
01:39:23,057 --> 01:39:26,185
[Monster Grunting]

1420
01:39:26,327 --> 01:39:29,228
- [Blind Man Laughing]
- [Monster Growling]

1421
01:39:29,330 --> 01:39:32,128
No, no.
This is good.

1422
01:39:32,232 --> 01:39:35,201
Smoke.
You try.

1423
01:39:36,303 --> 01:39:38,203
- Smoke.
- [Blind Man Laughs]

1424
01:39:38,305 --> 01:39:41,206
[Grunting Happily]

1425
01:39:44,945 --> 01:39:46,845
[Monster]
Mmm! Good! Good!

1426
01:39:46,947 --> 01:39:48,710
[Grunting, Chuckling]

1427
01:39:48,816 --> 01:39:51,512
Good...
[Coughs]

1428
01:39:51,618 --> 01:39:53,609
[Blind Man]
I was all alone.

1429
01:39:53,721 --> 01:39:56,053
It is bad to be alone.

1430
01:39:56,190 --> 01:39:59,921
Alone bad.

1431
01:40:00,027 --> 01:40:01,927
Friend good.

1432
01:40:02,029 --> 01:40:05,590
- Friend good!
- [Blind Man Laughs]

1433
01:40:05,699 --> 01:40:09,294
?? [Orchestra: Finale]

1434
01:40:09,403 --> 01:40:11,303
Time for bed, sport.

1435
01:40:13,741 --> 01:40:16,175
- [TV Off]
- What did you think of the movie?

1436
01:40:16,276 --> 01:40:17,675
Pretty cool.

1437
01:40:17,778 --> 01:40:20,838
- Better than most monster movies.
- Yeah?

1438
01:40:20,948 --> 01:40:22,916
I knew the guy who made it.

